  "context_summary": "26-year-old woman presenting with a new, persistent headache for 5 days that she describes as different from her usual headaches. It is worse in the mornings and when lying down, with no history of trauma. She has been taking a combined oral contraceptive pill for the past 2 years. The doctor has established the positional/postural character of the headache and its novelty relative to her baseline before screening for neurologic involvement.",
  "good_next_question": "Have you noticed any blurred or double vision, any weakness or numbness on one side, or any seizures or unusual episodes since the headache started?",
  "rationale": "This question screens for the focal neurologic deficits and seizure activity that separate a secondary intracranial process — here cerebral venous sinus thrombosis — from a primary headache disorder like migraine, which is the dangerous mimic this presentation pattern-matches to. The setup is a classic CVST profile: a young woman on a combined OCP (a major acquired prothrombotic factor) with a new positional headache worse when supine and in the morning, a pattern suggestive of raised intracranial pressure. A novice anchors on migraine because the demographics and headache fit, missing that the OCP plus a positional, progressively present headache is a venous-thrombosis red flag. Positive findings (visual changes from papilledema or sixth-nerve palsy, unilateral weakness/numbness, or seizures) substantially raise CVST/space-occupying probability and mandate urgent neuroimaging with venography (CT/MR venogram) rather than a triptan and reassurance. A negative answer does not exclude CVST given the prothrombotic context but keeps the workup appropriately broad. This question beats further characterizing pain quality because focal deficits and seizures are the features whose presence most decisively reroutes the patient toward emergent imaging.",
  "tags": [
    "headache",
    "young_female",
    "neurologic",
    "vascular",
    "red_flag_screen",
    "cvst"
  ],
